1.1 Motivating Example: SNAP Usage by ZIP Code

This graph shows a map of South Florida, upon which we have plotted the boundaries of all the Miami-Dade and Broward county ZIP Codes. Within these ZIP Code boundaries, weve plotted the proportion of households receiving food stamp / SNAP benefits (according to the 2016 Census).

Now, if youre not familiar with the tidyverse functions and data structures, that tibble thing may be unfamiliar to you. Basically, its like Rs version of an Excel spreadsheet. Lets find out what R considers the mpg object. We will use the str() function (it stands for the structure) to find out what R says about this mpg object.

The mpg object has three classes: tbl_df, tbl, and data.frame. The str() function is one of your most sleuthing powerful tools to troubleshoot your R code. Notice the $ symbol preceeding the column name. That is our method for selecting an individual column: data_frame$column_name.

1.4 The Tidy Data Style

Another thing to notice in our data frame is that each column is a variable and each row is a unique data point. This data format is known as tidy data, and this paper in the Journal of Statistical Software discusses why it is the most proper format to store rectangular data. Like we said earlier, a data.frame is similar to an Excel spreadsheet. We can also see the number of rows (234 obs.) and columns (11 variables) this data frame has, and the names of these columns.

2 Our First ggplot Graph

Now that we know a little about our data, we know that the variable displ stands for engine displacement in litres. This will be our measurement for the size of the engine. Further, we know that cty and hwy are the variables measuring city and highway MPG, respectively. With this information in hand, lets plot the relationship between engine size and highway MPG.

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point()

2.1 Three Components of a ggplot

There are three main components of the code to build this graph: the data argument, the mapping argument, and the geom_*() function. These components are organized in a logical manner and with a corresponding set of rules: these rules are called a grammar. Thats what the gg part stands for the grammar of graphics.

2.1.1 The data = Argument

The ggplot() function takes tidy data frames only. Using the str() function, we already confirmed that:

  • mpg is a dataframe, and
  • the mpg data frame is tidy (observations are rows, measurements are columns).

If you ever have trouble with ggplot(), make sure your data frame is tidy! If your data frame is not tidy, see this R-Bloggers post on using the reshape2:: or tidyr:: packages to format your data in a tidy manner.

2.1.2 mapping to an Aesthetic with aes()

We will talk about aesthetics in detail in the next section, but for now understand that mapping is how you tell ggplot() where your data goes. We are telling ggplot() to put engine size on the x-axis (x = displ) and highway fuel economy on the y-axis (y = hwy), all with the aes() function. As we will see in the next section, there are many more aesthetics we can map our measurements to.

2.1.3 The geom_*() Function

We told the ggplot() function where to find the data with the data = argument. We told the function which pieces we care about and how to related them with the aes() function to the mapping = argument. Now we need to tell ggplot() how to plot x and y. This is where the the geom_*() functions come into play: we wanted a scatterplot, so we picked geom_point(). Geom is short for geometric object, and there are quite a few geometric shapes we can bend our data into.

2.1.4 The Secret + Component

If you are more familiar with R, but not familiar with the tidyverse, then the idea of adding one function to another seems absurd. In the tidyverse world, however, think of this + sign as a way to add a layer to a graph. As youll see soon, we can add more and more to a single graph with this + operator.

Look back to the figure. You might notice that there is a group of five points that stick out: these cars have large engines but higher MPG than other vehicles with large engines. We could ask a few questions to try to explain this disparity:

  • Are these vehicles hybrids?
  • Do these vehicles use diesel?
  • Are these vehicles newer?

Each question is a hypothesis, and we will attempt to test these hypotheses visually in the next section.

3 Plotting Three (or More) Variables using Aesthetics

The ggplot() function allows us to add a third variable to a two-dimensional scatterplot by mapping this variable to an aesthetic. In our previous graph, the x-axis and y-axis were aesthetics, passed on to the ggplot() function through the aes() function. There are quite a few aesthetics to choose from to modify our scatterplot:

  • colour: What color to make our points? Good for continuous or discrete features.
  • size: How big should the points be? Better for continuous features.
  • alpha: How opaque / transparent should the points be? Values range from \([0,1]\), with \(1\) being completely opaque. Better for continuous features.
  • shape: What shape should the points have? Better for discrete features. Options are shown below
  • fill: For the shapes filled with red, what color should you put instead? Better for discrete features, but is limited when plotting points. The fill aesthetic truly shines with geoms other than point, but more on that later.

For most of these aesthetics, the behavior of the graph will change depending on if you map a discrete or continuous feature to it. For example, if you map a continuous feature, such as a numeric or interger feature, to the colour aesthetic, the points will be given a color gradient (by default, from dark blue to light blue). However, if you map a discrete value, such as a character or factor feature to the colour aesthetic, the points will be distinctly different in color.

3.1 Claim 1: Outlier Cars are Hybrids

Lets take a look at all the possible unique values for vehicle type. Remember that we can check the help documentation for the data set if were unsure of which column measures the type. Remember that we use the $ symbol to access a specific column of a data frame.

unique(mpg$class)
## [1] "compact"    "midsize"    "suv"        "2seater"    "minivan"   
## [6] "pickup"     "subcompact"

While we dont see hybrid in this list, we know that very few hybrid cars were in production in both 1998 and 2008. These cars would have all been classified as compact or sub-compact. Now what type of feature is class?

str(mpg$class)
##  chr [1:234] "compact" "compact" "compact" "compact" "compact" ...

The str() function informs us that this feature is a character feature, and therefore discrete. Therefore, we can add it to the graph with the colour or shape aesthetics.

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, colour = class)) + 
  geom_point()

It appears that our hypothesis was incorrect. These vehicles are not small, hybrid cars at all, but sportscars or midsize cars.

3.2 Claim 2: Outlier Cars take Diesel

Lets take a look at all the possible unique values for vehicle fuel. 

unique(mpg$fl)
## [1] "p" "r" "e" "d" "c"

This feature is a character feature. Because the fuel type is discrete, we can add it to the graph with the colour or shape aesthetics. 

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = fl)) + 
  geom_point()

Our hypothesis is incorrect. It appears that all five of our outlier vehicles take premium fuel, not diesel. This graph, when paired with the previous graph on car class, gives us a better understanding of factors that could influence the relationship between engine size and fuel economy.

3.3 Claim 3: Outlier Cars are Newer

We know that vehicle year can be either 1998 or 2008. Because the manufacture year is a time, we should add it to the graph with the colour, size or alpha aesthetics.

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, alpha = year)) + 
  geom_point()

The manufacture year doesnt help explain the five outlier points very well.

3.4 Updated Claim: Outlier Cars are Sportscars

We can add more than 3 features to a plot. Lets create an engine size by MPG plot with fuel type and car class added.

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, colour = class, shape = fl)) + 
  geom_point()

If youre thinking to yourself, I wish there was a way to clean this graph up, to only show the premium fuel and two-seater cars, then come back for the Data Manipulation with dplyr session! Not to fear, we will also discuss a way to break graphs into mutually-exclusive pieces, called facets, next.

4 Group by a Facet

Facets allow us to split our graphs over a categorical variable. Lets repeat the previous graph, but split over fuel type.

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, colour = class)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~ fl, nrow = 2)

We see a much stronger negative linear relationship between engine size and fuel economy for vehicles using regular petrol instead of premium.

Now what if we wanted facet on two features? Lets inspect how the number of cylinders in the engine, as well as the manufacturing year, affect the relationship between engine size and city fuel economy.

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = cty)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_grid(cyl ~ year) +
  coord_flip()

Notice that flipping the coordinates (via the coord_flip() command) allows use to see any differences in city fuel economy better. From this graph, the manufacture year doesnt seem to have much of an effect, other than that very small cars with four-cylinder engines lose a little fuel economy.

5 Shaping Up your Data with Geoms

As we mentioned in the Introduction, there are many Geoms we can use to plot our data. Lets compare two geoms, geom_point() and geom_smooth(). We can use the grid.arrange() function from the gridExtra:: package to put two plots side-by-side.

# install.packages("gridExtra")
library(gridExtra)
plot1 <- ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point()
plot2 <- ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_smooth()
grid.arrange(plot1, plot2, ncol=2)

We can also layer geoms on top of each other.

ggplot(data = mpg,
       mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(aes(colour = cyl)) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  geom_smooth(colour = "red")
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Notice that we are comparing the relationship between engine size and highway fuel economy while accounting for the number of cylinders effect, and overlaying the output from a linear model (blue) and a LOESS smoother (red).
